6:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-12","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Rate Mechanics"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Both Vertex and Drift use hourly funding rate calculations, making them suitable for short-term arbitrage strategies. Vertex's hybrid architecture allows for faster sequencer-based execution while maintaining on-chain settlement on Arbitrum. Drift's vAMM model with JIT liquidity provides dynamic pricing that can create more funding rate volatility. The key difference lies in settlement speed - Solana's sub-second finality versus Arbitrum's ~15 minute finality affects position timing strategies."}]]}]
7:["$","$Lb",null,{"items":[{"question":"Which exchange has better funding rate opportunities?","answer":"Both offer hourly funding intervals ideal for arbitrage. Vertex's cross-margin system provides better capital efficiency, while Drift's vAMM model can create more volatile funding rates with higher profit potential."},{"question":"How do transaction costs compare for funding arbitrage?","answer":"Vertex has lower taker fees (0.03% vs 0.05%) but Arbitrum gas costs. Drift benefits from Solana's ultra-low transaction fees. For high-frequency arbitrage, Drift's cost structure is typically superior."},{"question":"Which platform handles liquidations better for leveraged positions?","answer":"Vertex uses simpler cross-margin liquidation mechanics that are easier to predict. Drift's complex liquidation system with insurance fund provides better protection but requires deeper understanding of the mechanics."},{"question":"How do settlement speeds affect arbitrage strategies?","answer":"Drift's sub-second Solana finality enables rapid position adjustments critical for funding rate arbitrage. Vertex's Arbitrum settlement takes longer but offers more predictable execution for planned strategies."}]}]
